Both paths can lead to fulfilling careers but only if they match the personality. Neither way is better or worse as long as you are going the route that makes you happiest. Going the wrong path hurts all involved

My advice for my children is to finish their education, take 2 years or so at a large company and then decide if they want that incrementally improving life style or if they to build something from scratch for the chance of outsized gains. I expect each to choose a different path

At different times in your career, they may or may not be the right kind of place for you as your risk profile or life goals change. IMO, earlier in your career, it’s easier, because the potential gains outweigh the risk. Harder to do later when a family depends on stability

I am differentiating between a job at an established company and a startup. Startups usually pay less so more can be reinvested into growth and because the gains come later. A startup depends on everyone sacrificing for the good of the group. They are not for everyone

Imo, joining a startup is like having a child. You don’t ignore that child to go play with other kids that are different from yours. You raise it to maturity. If that’s not for you, there are lots of other company types to work for.
So, in your mind, are you meant to spend all of your energy in your job? Unable to do personal projects in your free time because that shows you're not committed?

You may be right. After pouring heart, soul, and personal time into a number of orgs and not seeing the upside, I’m hesitant to do that again. But perhaps those weren’t true startup situations. Live and learn.
If you have time to do wacky stuff, then you aren’t committed to the startup and should move on

Even if I'm at a startup, there's crazy wacky stuff I want to make that no company is going to be interested in. Let me make it, have a shot. Let me have that validation of shipping. Maybe I'll get a few sales? Maybe I'll get a ton? Why squash that?

In my mind it’s a matter structure and expectation. If you’re a startup, then all energies should be invested there, especially if you share in the success. If you’re cruising along at place like EA or Activision then maybe external work is fine

It seems that some number of orgs are modernizing and loosening up the leash a bit. Trying to gather data and find out the specifics. The old ways are so wasteful and demoralizing. It’s one area that the indies are definitely leading the way and promoting innovation
DM'd sir. That's potentially the most concise summary I've ever done for anything.
Any details you can share either instance are appreciated. DM if necessary
SO IT'S ALL OVER THE PLACE. LightBox Interactive (Starhawk, since shuttered) working with Sony Santa Monica was the most encouraging of side-projects that I've worked for.

I've worked at companies that encourage you to work on your own projects and companies (well, singular) that not only wanted to own the project but also sued for a portion of the revenue by a project I was working on when I left.

I think that depends on your employment contract. I’ve never heard of a game company allowing it without approval and all work is owned by the company unless they give you a waiver otherwise. The EU has different rules than US so not representative
Thank you for the info! And if there was a conflict, did the company assume ownership of the concept or any work done, or just advise the employee to stop work?
We always allowed this at Four Door Lemon (and @CoopInnovations ) but would did have to give approval first to ensure no conflicts with anything studio or client wise.
